## LightLogR 0.9.2 Sunrise: your priorities implemented

Here are some of the highlights in LightLogR 0.9.2 Sunrise, with even
more to be found in the
[changelog](https://tscnlab.github.io/LightLogR/news/index.html#lightlogr-091).

Photoperiod support

Simply provide the coordinates of your data collection to add
information on sunrise, sunset, and the duration of the photoperiod to
your analysis:

- [add_photoperiod()](https://tscnlab.github.io/LightLogR/reference/photoperiod.html)
  adds photoperiod information to your dataset
- [extract_photoperiod()](https://tscnlab.github.io/LightLogR/reference/photoperiod.html)
  provides a succinct summary for photoperiod on all relevant days
  contained in a dataset
- [gg_photoperiod()](https://tscnlab.github.io/LightLogR/reference/gg_photoperiod.html)
  adds shaded areas for nighttimes in plots

Mind the gaps

Five new functions for complete and regular time series resolve
frustrations many of you highlighted.

- [gap_table()](https://tscnlab.github.io/LightLogR/reference/gap_table.html)
  for a clean summary of available and missing data
- [has_gaps()](https://tscnlab.github.io/LightLogR/reference/has_gaps.html),
  [has_irregulars()](https://tscnlab.github.io/LightLogR/reference/has_irregulars.html),
  and
  [extract_gaps()](https://tscnlab.github.io/LightLogR/reference/extract_gaps.html)
  for quick assessments
- [remove_partial_data()](https://tscnlab.github.io/LightLogR/reference/remove_partial_data.html)
  to remove groups with insufficient data
- [gg_gaps()](https://tscnlab.github.io/LightLogR/reference/gg_gaps.html)
  to visualize where gaps and irregular data occur

Spectral analysis

Three new functions to reconstruct and integrate across light spectra
for multi-spectral devices.

- [spectral_reconstruction()](https://tscnlab.github.io/LightLogR/reference/spectral_reconstruction.html)
  returns spectral irradiances with the help of a calibration matrix
- [spectral_integration()](https://tscnlab.github.io/LightLogR/reference/spectral_integration.html)
  integrates over the spectrum, either fully or in parts, optionally
  with action spectra and weighing factors
- [normalize_counts()](https://tscnlab.github.io/LightLogR/reference/normalize_counts.html)
  normalize raw counts based on sensor outputs and a gain value.

Rock-solid & reproducible

How many stars can you count in this newsletter? Well, ten times as many
unit tests, **888** to be specific, ensure that the functions in
LightLogR have consistent output, and remain so even with future
changes.

Continuous integration, and three [new
tutorials](https://tscnlab.github.io/LightLogR/articles/) ensure
analysis with transparent, accessible, and standardized pipelines.

Broader device support

Weve added more import wrappers and are now supporting 18 different
devices and counting. See the list of supported devices
[here](https://tscnlab.github.io/LightLogR/reference/import_Dataset.html#devices).
Let us know of any other device that should join the list.

More metrics

We are continuously expanding on the [number of
metrics](https://tscnlab.github.io/LightLogR/index.html#metrics-1) we
support with a consistent interface and have rewritten the tutorial on
[metrics](https://tscnlab.github.io/LightLogR/articles/Metrics.html)
because the new functionality of LightLogR makes metric summaries even
easier and more flexible.

Notable additions are functions to mark up or extract special conditions
from your dataset:

- [add_clusters()](https://tscnlab.github.io/LightLogR/reference/extract_clusters.html)
  and
  [extract_clusters()](https://tscnlab.github.io/LightLogR/reference/extract_clusters.html)
  find clusters of data, where conditions hold for a specified duration.
- [extract_states()](https://tscnlab.github.io/LightLogR/reference/extract_states.html)
  summarises states in your data
- [summarize_numeric()](https://tscnlab.github.io/LightLogR/reference/summarize_numeric.html)/[summarise_numeric()](https://tscnlab.github.io/LightLogR/reference/summarize_numeric.html)
  is a quick way to calculate averages across many groups
- [mean_daily()](https://tscnlab.github.io/LightLogR/reference/mean_daily.html)
  calculates average values for weekdays, weekends, and a
  weekday/weeken-weighted average

Dealing with many zero values in measurements of light exposure data can
also be a challenge for logarithmis transformation. The pair of
zero-inflation functions
[log_zero_inflated()](https://tscnlab.github.io/LightLogR/reference/log_zero_inflated.html)
and
[exp_zero_inflated()](https://tscnlab.github.io/LightLogR/reference/exp_zero_inflated.html)
help to deal with this issue in a principled way.

##### We are very happy to see so many researchers from so many disciplines utilising LightLogR in their work and we are eager to support you along this journey to further empower your data and build meaningful insights.

## GLEE: a new chapter

The *Translational Sensory & Circadian Neuroscience Unit
(MPS/TUM/TUMCREATE)* is launching **GLEE**, an open-source reimagining
how light exposure data is collected, stored, processed, and analyzed.

[![](data:image/png;base64,)](https://www.visualdiet.org/)

------------------------------------------------------------------------

### The vision

GLEE will foster knowledge exchange and drive advancements beyond the
capabilities of any single research group.

### Community impact

With a focus on collaboration and engagement, GLEE aims to build a
legacy of innovation and progress in understanding and managing the
health impacts of global light exposure.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

### Join the GLEE journey

Be part of this groundbreaking initiative that will transform light
exposure research. GLEE represents our commitment to open science and
collaborative research methodologies that benefit the entire scientific
community.

Global collaboration

Connect with researchers worldwide working on light exposure studies.

Open-source database

Access standardized light exposure data from diverse populations and
environments.

Shared resources

Benefit from community-developed analysis tools and methodologies.

------------------------------------------------------------------------
